eLSA installation using conda on University of Arizona HPC

I recommend getting familiar with basic Linux commands.
https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/linux-commands

If you do not have a UArizona HPC account. Follow this link to create one. 
https://public.confluence.arizona.edu/display/UAHPC/Account+Creation#AccountCreation-SponsoredHPCAccountInstructions

Input Paul Carini’s email(paulcarini@arizona.edu) for a sponsor request.
Log in with your net ID to set up an account

Mac Users:
Open Terminal and ssh into the Uarizona HPC with your UArizona HPC username and password

Example

 
Type “shell”. This will automatically connect you to the Puma cluster

We are going to install a conda using an interactive session
(puma) [christinagb@wentletrap ~]$ interactive -a paulcarini
1.	Activate conda
conda activate
2.	Create and name the conda environment with python 2.7
conda create –name elsa python=2.7
3.	Activate the conda environment
conda activate elsa
4.	Retrieve the elsa files from Hannah Holland-Moritz’ github and rename directory
wget -O elsa.zip https://github.com/hhollandmoritz/elsa/archive/84b7a742a70a1b2a8490b3d31cbe1df3b89d5fd8.zip Unzip the files
Unzip main.zip
5.	Go into the new elsa directory
cd elsa_conda_env-main
Check to make sure we have the correct version of Python. Should be Python 2.7.15
python –version
6.	Input the following commands one by one and enter after each line
pip install –upgrade pip
pip install pyserial
pip install version_utils
pip install scipy
python setup.py


